No doubt inevitable.††

All politicians, well intentioned or not, seek to raise revenues, via taxes, in the least politically impactive way.† Governor Perdue, in raising taxes on tobacco and alcohol, follows a road well traveled in years gone by, joining the ranks of other ineffective, and to some extent gutless,†leaders of our state.

Of course taxing tobacco comes with all sorts of seemingly viable arguments.† Smoking leads to all sorts of health issues which stress the healthcare system across the spectrum.† Some of these stresses hit the state directly through Medicaid and other programs.† Others affect us all through higher insurance costs, doctor's fees , etc.† If these stresses, costs, are so impactive as to require remedial action, then outlawing smoking is the appropriate solution.† Politically, of course, that tends to make†one-time Governors.† The more insidious way is to continually raise taxes.† Maybe the ultimate goal can be reached and the state, and the feds as well, can make a few bucks along the way.† Never pass up a chance to make money while doing socially good things.

Any amateur observer can see that the bulk of smokers are those of lesser means.† Over the years anti-smoking campaigns and education have led the more affluent and better educated to abandon smoking.† Chances are that over time the smoking†population will continue to decline without any new taxes or prohibition laws.† One can hardly argue that raising taxes on smoking won't hasten that decline.† In the interim, however, Governor Perdue seeks to balance her budget on the backs of those still "sinning".† The demographics would appear to suggest that this is a politically safe risk.

Now you can't make the same argument about alcohol.† Most recent studies have suggested that a regular, moderate use of alcohol improves health.† If health costs are to be our justification for raising revenues, in a targeted way, then reason would proffer that we should decrease taxes on alcohol.† Blasphemy!† That increases the budget problem.† That can't be a good idea.

We have this process called the "income tax".† It's structured in a†progressive manner so increases could be directed at those who can better afford to pay, either by raising the higher rates or through surtaxes on higher incomes.† Here comes the clatter about†"class warfare".† Baloney!† When times are tough, those with means should be called upon to help out "not only†in proportion to their†revenue, but something†more than in that proportion".† Read your Adam Smith.

The fact that we're seeking to raise taxes period negates any argument about raising taxes in a recession.† Since elected officials are elected to look out for the welfare of all our citizens, most especially in the Democratic view, those who need the most help, raising taxes that essentially impact low and/or middle income†earners, appears contrary to that view.† In our culture we honor, just as much, if not more so, those whose heroism ended in their demise, as those who lived to†fight another day.† Might be time for a little more "valor" on the part of all our elected officials.† Could we start with the Governor?†


